words.meaning: Fluent or persuasive in speaking or writing.
examples: The president gave an eloquent speech about unity.
She was an eloquent advocate for animal rights.

words.meaning: To make (something) clear; explain.
examples: The professor used a diagram to elucidate the complex theory.
Could you please elucidate your point for me?

words.meaning: To escape from or avoid (a danger, enemy, or pursuer), typically in a skillful or cunning way.
examples: The suspect managed to elude the police for several weeks.
The meaning of the poem continues to elude me.

words.meaning: Difficult to find, catch, or achieve.
examples: The elusive snow leopard is rarely seen in the wild.
Success can be an elusive goal.

words.meaning: Relating to or characteristic of heaven or paradise.
examples: The island was an Elysian paradise with white sandy beaches.
They lived in Elysian bliss for a few short years.

words.meaning: Abnormally thin or weak, especially because of illness or a lack of food.
examples: The emaciated stray dog was clearly starving.
After weeks of being lost in the desert, he was emaciated.

words.meaning: (Of a feeling, quality, or sensation) issuing or spreading out from (a source).
examples: A strange light was emanating from the old house.
He had an aura of confidence emanating from him.

words.meaning: To set free, especially from legal, social, or political restrictions.
examples: The new law was intended to emancipate the slaves.
She felt emancipated from the constraints of her old life.

words.meaning: To make (something) more attractive by the addition of decorative details or features.
examples: She embellished the dress with colorful beads.
He tends to embellish his stories to make them more exciting.

words.meaning: To hold (someone) closely in one's arms, especially as a sign of affection; to accept or support (a belief, theory, or change) willingly and enthusiastically.
examples: She embraced her long-lost brother.
The company was slow to embrace new technology.

words.meaning: To involve (someone) deeply in an argument, conflict, or difficult situation.
examples: He became embroiled in a legal battle with his former business partner.
The country was embroiled in a civil war.

words.meaning: Past tense of embroil; involved deeply in an argument, conflict, or difficult situation.
examples: The senator was embroiled in a scandal.
She had no desire to get embroiled in their personal arguments.

words.meaning: (Of a system, idea, or organization) in a rudimentary stage with potential for development.
examples: The project is still in its embryonic stage.
The company had an embryonic idea for a new product.

words.meaning: (Of a person) famous and respected within a particular sphere or profession.
examples: He is an eminent scientist who has won many awards.
The lecture was given by an eminent historian.

words.meaning: A person sent on a special mission, usually as a diplomatic representative.
examples: The king sent an emissary to negotiate a peace treaty.
She acted as an emissary for the company in the trade talks.

words.meaning: To produce and discharge (something, especially gas or radiation).
examples: The factory was emitting toxic fumes into the air.
The flowers emit a sweet fragrance.

words.meaning: Having the quality of softening or soothing the skin; attempting to avoid confrontation or anger; soothing or calming.
examples: The lotion has an emollient effect on dry skin.
He spoke in a calm and emollient tone.

words.meaning: Showing an ability to understand and share the feelings of another.
examples: She is an empathetic person who is always there for her friends.
A good therapist must be empathetic to their clients' needs.

words.meaning: Showing or giving emphasis; expressing something forcibly and clearly.
examples: She gave an emphatic denial of the accusations.
He was emphatic that he would not change his mind.

words.meaning: Based on, concerned with, or verifiable by observation or experience rather than theory or pure logic.
examples: The scientist gathered empirical evidence to support his theory.
The study was based on empirical research.

words.meaning: The theory that all knowledge is derived from sense-experience.
examples: The scientific method is based on the principles of empiricism.
He was a firm believer in empiricism and rejected all forms of superstition.

words.meaning: To match or surpass (a person or achievement), typically by imitation.
examples: He tried to emulate his favorite basketball player.
She hopes to emulate the success of her older sister.

words.meaning: To fill (someone) with great delight; charm.
examples: The beautiful music enchanted the audience.
She was enchanted by his wit and good looks.

words.meaning: A speech or piece of writing that praises someone or something highly.
examples: The retiring professor received a heartfelt encomium from his colleagues.
The book is an encomium to the bravery of the soldiers.

words.meaning: To surround and have or hold within; to include comprehensively.
examples: The national park encompasses a vast wilderness area.
The course will encompass all aspects of modern history.

words.meaning: To intrude on (a person's territory or a thing considered to be a right).
examples: The new development will encroach on the protected wetland.
I don't want to encroach on your personal time.

words.meaning: Intruding on (a person's territory or a thing considered to be a right).
examples: The encroaching desert is a threat to the local ecosystem.
She felt that his questions were encroaching on her privacy.

words.meaning: To restrict or burden (someone or something) in such a way that free action or movement is difficult.
examples: He was encumbered by a heavy backpack.
The company was encumbered with debt.

words.meaning: A burden or impediment.
examples: He saw his large family as an encumbrance to his career.
The lack of funding was a major encumbrance to the project.

words.meaning: Having or showing comprehensive knowledge.
examples: He has an encyclopedic knowledge of history.
The book is an encyclopedic guide to the world's birds.

words.meaning: To try hard to do or achieve something.
examples: We must endeavor to find a peaceful solution to the conflict.
She endeavored to learn the new language.

words.meaning: (Of a disease or condition) regularly found among particular people or in a certain area.
examples: Malaria is endemic in many tropical countries.
Corruption is endemic in the country's political system.

words.meaning: To declare one's public approval or support of.
examples: The newspaper endorsed the candidate for president.
Many celebrities endorse products for a fee.

words.meaning: To provide with a quality, ability, or asset.
examples: She was endowed with a beautiful singing voice.
The wealthy philanthropist endowed a new hospital wing.

words.meaning: Feeling drained of energy or vitality; weakened.
examples: After the long hike, he felt completely enervated.
The enervated patient could barely sit up in bed.

words.meaning: Causing one to feel drained of energy or vitality.
examples: The hot, humid weather was enervating.
He found the repetitive work to be enervating.

words.meaning: To cause or give rise to (a feeling, situation, or condition).
examples: The politician's speech engendered a great deal of controversy.
The new policy is intended to engender a sense of community.

words.meaning: Having all one's attention or interest absorbed by someone or something.
examples: She was so engrossed in her book that she didn't hear the phone ring.
The children were engrossed in the cartoon.

words.meaning: To intensify, increase, or further improve the quality, value, or extent of.
examples: The new software will enhance the security of the system.
She used makeup to enhance her natural beauty.

words.meaning: A person or thing that is mysterious, puzzling, or difficult to understand.
examples: The cause of the disease remains an enigma to scientists.
He was a complex and enigmatic character.

words.meaning: Difficult to interpret or understand; mysterious.
examples: She gave an enigmatic smile.
The novel has an enigmatic ending that is open to interpretation.

words.meaning: To instruct or urge (someone) to do something.
examples: The doctor enjoined her patient to get more rest.
The judge enjoined the company from selling the faulty product.

words.meaning: To enroll or be enrolled in the armed services.
examples: He decided to enlist in the army after graduating from high school.
The organization is trying to enlist volunteers to help with the project.

words.meaning: The state or feeling of being actively opposed or hostile to someone or something.
examples: There was a long history of enmity between the two families.
He felt a deep enmity towards his rival.

words.meaning: A feeling of listlessness and dissatisfaction arising from a lack of occupation or excitement.
examples: The long, rainy afternoon was filled with ennui.
He suffered from a sense of ennui and purposelessness.

words.meaning: The great or extreme scale, seriousness, or extent of something perceived as bad or morally wrong.
examples: The world was shocked by the enormity of the crime.
The full enormity of the disaster was not yet known.

words.meaning: A flag or standard, especially a military or naval one indicating nationality.
examples: The ship flew the ensign of its country.
The soldier proudly carried the regimental ensign.

words.meaning: To capture the fascinated attention of.
examples: The storyteller's magical tales would enthral the children for hours.
She was enthralled by the beauty of the landscape.

words.meaning: To capture the fascinated attention of.
examples: The audience was enthralled by the performance.
I was enthralled by her charismatic personality.

words.meaning: To attract or tempt by offering pleasure or advantage.
examples: The store tried to entice customers with a big sale.
He was enticed by the promise of a large reward.

words.meaning: Believing oneself to be inherently deserving of privileges or special treatment.
examples: He felt entitled to a promotion, even though he had not earned it.
The entitled celebrity demanded special treatment.

words.meaning: The fact of having a right to something; the belief that one is inherently deserving of privileges or special treatment.
examples: She had a strong sense of entitlement and expected to get whatever she wanted.
Access to healthcare should be a right, not an entitlement.

words.meaning: The branch of zoology concerned with the study of insects.
examples: He is a professor of entomology at the university.
Her interest in entomology began when she was a child.

words.meaning: A group of people attending or surrounding an important person.
examples: The rock star arrived with a large entourage of assistants and bodyguards.
The president's entourage included several advisors and aides.

words.meaning: To ask someone earnestly or anxiously to do something.
examples: He entreated her to forgive him.
She entreated him not to go.

words.meaning: An earnest or humble request.
examples: He made a passionate entreaty for peace.
She ignored his entreaties to stay.

words.meaning: (Of an attitude, habit, or belief) firmly established and difficult or unlikely to change; ingrained.
examples: It is difficult to change such entrenched attitudes.
The company has an entrenched position in the market.

words.meaning: To mention (a number of things) one by one.
examples: She enumerated the reasons why she was against the proposal.
The report enumerates the various problems with the current system.

words.meaning: To say or pronounce clearly.
examples: It is important to enunciate your words when speaking in public.
The teacher asked the student to enunciate more clearly.

words.meaning: Lasting for a very short time.
examples: The beauty of the cherry blossoms is ephemeral.
Fame can be ephemeral.
